{
    "analysis": "From the prior Executor output we loaded metric/trace/log data and filtered metric rows to the candidate set of known nodes/services/pods. There are 56 matched cmdb_id values (examples include adservice, frontend-0, frontend-1, frontend-2, etc.), totaling 4,989 distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs. The filtered metric_candidates table has shape 303,547 rows x 5 columns. Trace and log data also cover the incident window (trace: 12:00–12:29 UTC+8; log: 12:00–12:30 UTC+8). error_logs.csv is empty. Next, per the workflow, we must compute global thresholds for each candidate 'component-KPI' time series using the full available series (before filtering to the incident window). These thresholds (e.g., global P95 and P5) are required prior to extracting incident-time slices for anomaly detection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel variable 'metric_candidates' (all rows for matched cmdb_ids), compute global summary statistics for each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair WITHOUT filtering by incident time. For each pair calculate: sample count, mean, std, min, max, P95 (95th percentile), and P5 (5th percentile). Store the full result in a kernel variable named 'component_kpi_thresholds'. Then return a compact table with the top 20 rows sorted by severity = abs(P95 - mean) / (abs(mean) + 1e-9) in descending order. The returned columns should be: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count, mean, std, min, max, p95, p5, severity. Keep output bounded to these top 20 rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global statistics (including P95 and P5) for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair across the full available metric series and stored them in 'component_kpi_thresholds'. The top severity pairs include many container fs/cpu/memory-related KPIs and some node-level I/O KPIs, which suggests resource or I/O abnormalities are plausible. The next required step (per the workflow) is to extract the incident-window metric data and detect anomalies relative to the previously computed global thresholds so we can identify candidate faults (consecutive anomaly runs) during 2022-03-21 12:00–12:30 (UTC+8). No trace/log analysis has been done yet; error_logs.csv is empty so logs will be limited to log.csv. ",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter the kernel variable 'metric_candidates' to the incident time window 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 12:30:00+08:00 and store the result in 'metric_incident'. Then join 'metric_incident' with 'component_kpi_thresholds' on (cmdb_id, kpi_name) to attach p95, p5, and mean. Create anomaly flags per row: 'anomaly_high' = value >= p95, 'anomaly_low' = value <= p5. Store the joined table in kernel variable 'metric_anomalies'. Next, for each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) in 'metric_anomalies' compute compact aggregates: total_anomalies (count of rows where anomaly_high or anomaly_low), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp where anomaly occurs), anomaly_type (\"high\" if only anomaly_high seen, \"low\" if only anomaly_low seen, \"both\" if both), and longest_consecutive_anomaly_streak_in_minutes (compute longest run of consecutive minute timestamps where anomaly flag is True). Also include mean, p95, p5 in the aggregate. Store full per-pair anomalies summary in 'component_kpi_anomaly_summary'. Return only the top 20 rows sorted by total_anomalies descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8, anomaly_type, longest_consecutive_anomaly_streak_minutes, mean, p95, p5. Keep output bounded to these 20 rows."}

{
    "analysis": "You filtered metrics to the incident window and joined per-row global thresholds, producing per-row anomaly flags and a per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomaly summary. The anomaly summary shows many component-KPI pairs with anomalies at every minute of the 31-minute window (total_anomalies = 31) and earliest anomaly at 12:00:00+08. Top noisy pairs include shippingservice2-0 mesh.* series and many adservice KPIs (app.grpc/app.http and JVM/runtime metrics), and several container memory/fs/cpu KPIs where p95==p5 (constant values), causing 'both' anomaly flags. This suggests a broad, continuous anomaly affecting multiple KPIs and components starting at the window start (12:00). To localize the root cause component we must aggregate per-component (cmdb_id) to find which components have the most distinct KPIs anomalous, which have anomalies across many minutes, and which show earliest occurrences. This will let us narrow to node vs. container vs. service candidates before using traces/logs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Aggregate 'component_kpi_anomaly_summary' to produce a per-component summary and store it as 'component_anomaly_summary'. For each cmdb_id compute: (a) distinct_anomalous_kpis = count of distinct kpi_name with total_anomalies>0; (b) total_anomaly_points = sum of total_anomalies across its KPIs; (c) earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8 = min of earliest_anomaly_timestamp across its KPIs; (d) max_consecutive_streak_minutes = max of longest_consecutive_anomaly_streak_minutes across its KPIs; (e) full_window_kpi_count = count of KPIs with longest_consecutive_anomaly_streak_minutes equal to 31 (full window). Return only the top 20 components sorted by distinct_anomalous_kpis descending, then by total_anomaly_points descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, distinct_anomalous_kpis, total_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8, max_consecutive_streak_minutes, full_window_kpi_count. Keep the output compact (<=20 rows)." 
}

{
    "analysis": "You aggregated metric anomalies per component and found a broad, continuous anomaly pattern beginning at 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08:00 affecting many services and pods. adservice (and its pods) is the top component by distinct anomalous KPIs (341 KPIs, 297 KPIs anomalous across the full 31-min window), and many other services/pods show full-window anomalies as well. This wide coverage implies either a widespread infrastructure problem (node-level or network) or a cascading service-level failure affecting many downstream metrics. To decide between node/container/service causes and to pick the most downstream faulty component (per rules), we must analyze traces next (to find call chains, identify which faulty components are downstream in traces) and/or check trace-level anomalies (e.g., duration increases or error-related trace metrics). We have not yet computed global thresholds for trace metrics, nor checked trace anomalies during the incident window, which is the next logical step to localize the root cause among the many metric-flagged components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Compute global statistics for trace.csv per (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the full available trace series (no incident filtering). For each pair compute: count, mean, std, min, max, p95, p5. Store full result in kernel variable 'trace_thresholds'. Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 12:30:00+08:00, join with 'trace_thresholds' to attach p95 and mean, and flag per-row 'trace_anomaly_high' when value >= p95. Store joined table in 'trace_anomalies'. Finally aggregate 'trace_anomalies' per cmdb_id producing: total_trace_anomaly_points (count of trace_anomaly_high True), distinct_trace_names_with_anomaly, earliest_trace_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8 (min timestamp where anomaly occurs). Return only the top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by total_trace_anomaly_points descending, with columns: cmdb_id, total_trace_anomaly_points, distinct_trace_names_with_anomaly, earliest_trace_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8. Keep output bounded to these 20 rows and store intermediate tables as requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "So far we have: 1) computed global thresholds for all metric (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs and identified per-minute anomalies in the incident window (2022-03-21 12:00–12:30+08). 2) Aggregated metric anomalies per component: adservice (and its pods) show the largest number of distinct anomalous KPIs (adservice: 341 KPIs, 297 KPIs anomalous for the full 31-min window) and many other services/pods (frontend*, checkoutservice*, productcatalogservice*, shippingservice*, etc.) also show full-window anomalies beginning at 12:00:00+08. 3) Computed trace global thresholds and incident-window trace anomalies: trace-level anomalies are concentrated in checkoutservice and frontend pods (checkoutservice-0/1/2, frontend-0/1/2, etc.), with earliest trace anomalies at 12:00:00+08. These results indicate a broad, continuous anomaly across many components starting exactly at the window start. However, metric and trace top-lists differ (metrics point strongly to adservice; traces point strongly to checkoutservice/frontend). According to the diagnosis rules, we should prioritize components that are anomalous in multiple modalities (metrics + traces) and then use trace call-chain ordering to pick the most downstream faulty component among them. To proceed we need a compact cross-modal summary listing components that are faulty in metrics and also show trace anomalies, with counts and earliest timestamps, so we can narrow candidates for root cause localization and then inspect traces/logs for downstream position and resource-specific reasons.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Produce a cross-modal compact summary by joining the per-component metric anomaly summary ('component_anomaly_summary') with the trace-anomaly aggregation (the per-cmdb_id trace summary). For each cmdb_id present in either source, compute and return up to top 20 rows sorted by distinct_anomalous_kpis (metric) descending, then by total_trace_anomaly_points descending. Columns to return: cmdb_id, distinct_anomalous_kpis (use 0 if missing), total_anomaly_points (metric; use 0 if missing), earliest_metric_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8 (NaT if missing), total_trace_anomaly_points (use 0 if missing), distinct_trace_names_with_anomaly (use 0 if missing), earliest_trace_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8 (NaT if missing). Store the full joined table in kernel variable 'component_multi_modal_summary'. Keep output compact (<=20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection for metrics and traces. Key findings so far: metric anomalies are extremely broad and continuous across the full 31-minute window starting at 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08:00 — adservice (and its pods) shows the largest number of distinct anomalous KPIs, with many KPIs anomalous for the full window. Trace anomalies are concentrated in frontend and checkoutservice pods (checkoutservice-0/1/2, frontend-0/1/2, etc.) with earliest trace anomalies at 12:00:00+08:00. The cross-modal summary shows many components have both metric and trace anomalies (e.g., frontend and checkoutservice pods), while adservice has strong metric anomalies but no trace anomalies. According to the diagnosis rules, we should now use trace call-chain information to identify which faulty service/pod is most downstream among the metric-flagged components (components that are anomalous in metrics and also show trace anomalies). To do that we need to (a) enumerate components that are anomalous in both metrics and traces, and (b) inspect the trace_name values observed for those components in the incident window to understand directional call relationships (caller->callee) so we can determine downstream order. This is the next necessary step before drilling into logs or specific resource KPIs for reason identification.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Identify components that show anomalies in BOTH metrics and traces during the incident window by using the kernel variable 'component_multi_modal_summary'. Return a compact result with:\n1) total count of components with distinct_anomalous_kpis>0 AND total_trace_anomaly_points>0.\n2) Up to 20 such cmdb_id values sorted by distinct_anomalous_kpis descending (include the two columns: distinct_anomalous_kpis and total_trace_anomaly_points).\nFor each returned cmdb_id, also provide up to 20 distinct trace_name values observed in the incident-window trace data (use the kernel variable 'trace_incident' or 'trace_anomalies' as available). Keep outputs compact (limit rows/strings as requested). Store the list of identified multi-modal components in kernel variable 'multi_modal_candidates' for subsequent trace-call-chain analysis."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection for metrics and traces. Metrics show broad, continuous anomalies across many components starting at 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08, with adservice (and its pods) having the largest number of distinct anomalous KPIs. Trace anomalies are concentrated on frontend and checkoutservice pods (earliest trace anomalies also at 12:00:00+08). We also produced a compact list of components that are anomalous in BOTH metrics and traces (about 40 multi-modal candidates). According to the diagnosis rules, the next step is trace call-chain analysis to determine which of these multi-modal faulty components are the most downstream in call chains (the root cause should be the most downstream faulty component within traces). We therefore need to extract incident-window trace records for the multi-modal candidates, parse trace_name patterns (e.g., 'trace.from_<source>...') to identify caller->callee relationships, and produce a compact per-component summary of incoming callers (distinct 'from' sources) and earliest trace anomaly times. This will let us rank candidate components by how downstream they are and prioritize which faulty component is the likely root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel variables 'multi_modal_candidates' (list of cmdb_id) and 'trace_incident' (incident-window trace rows), analyze call relationships for those candidates as follows and store results in 'trace_call_relations':\n1) Filter trace_incident to rows whose cmdb_id is in 'multi_modal_candidates'.\n2) For each filtered row, parse trace_name and extract a caller/source token when trace_name matches the pattern 'trace.from_<source>.' (extract '<source>' including any suffix like '-0'); ignore trace_names that do not follow 'trace.from_' pattern. Create a column 'trace_from'.\n3) Aggregate per cmdb_id: compute distinct_from_count = number of distinct 'trace_from' sources (exclude nulls), sample_from_list = up to 10 distinct 'trace_from' values, total_trace_rows = count of filtered trace rows for this cmdb_id, and earliest_trace_row_timestamp_UTC+8 = minimum timestamp among its filtered rows.\n4) Return a compact table of up to 20 rows sorted by distinct_from_count descending, with columns: cmdb_id, distinct_from_count, sample_from_list, total_trace_rows, earliest_trace_row_timestamp_UTC+8. Also store the full per-row parsed table in kernel variable 'trace_incident_parsed' for later inspection. Keep outputs bounded as requested."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and anomaly detection across metrics and traces and parsed trace call relationships. Findings so far: metric anomalies are broad and continuous from 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08 across many services; adservice shows the largest count of distinct anomalous KPIs (strong metric signal) but had no trace anomalies. Trace anomalies concentrate on frontend and checkoutservice pods, and trace call parsing shows a clear call chain pattern: frontend -> checkoutservice -> downstream services such as productcatalogservice. Productcatalogservice-0/1/2 are anomalous in both metrics and traces (each shows ~120 distinct anomalous KPIs and earliest traces at 12:00:00+08), and they receive calls from many upstream services (highest distinct caller count = 11). According to the diagnostics rules, the root cause for a single failure is most likely the most downstream faulty component within trace call chains among the metric-flagged components. Productcatalogservice pods are downstream of checkoutservice and frontend and are faulty in both metrics and traces, making them high-priority root-cause candidates. To identify the precise root cause component and reason (resource type), we need to inspect which KPIs (resource types) for productcatalogservice pods breached thresholds during the incident (e.g., container CPU, memory, fs IO, or node-level I/O). This per-KPI view will let us determine the resource reason (container CPU/memory/I/O, node disk, etc.) and the exact first anomalous timestamp.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomaly summary ('component_kpi_anomaly_summary'), extract all rows for cmdb_id in [\"productcatalogservice-0\",\"productcatalogservice-1\",\"productcatalogservice-2\",\"productcatalogservice\",\"productcatalogservice2-0\"] (include the service-level entry if present). For these rows produce a compact table (limit to top 20 rows) sorted by total_anomalies descending, showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_anomalies, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_UTC+8, anomaly_type, longest_consecutive_anomaly_streak_minutes, mean, p95, p5. Store the filtered full set in kernel variable 'productcatalog_kpi_anomalies'. Return only the top 20 rows as the result." 
}

{
    "analysis": "You categorized productcatalogservice KPIs and found multiple resource categories with continuous anomalies across the full incident window (2022-03-21 12:00:00+08 to 12:30:00+08). Key observations: (1) fs_io category shows many KPI pairs and the largest full-window anomaly counts, indicating persistent I/O-related signals; (2) memory and cpu categories also show anomalies but with fewer KPI pairs than fs_io; (3) many KPI series have identical mean/p95/p5 (constant-valued), causing 'both' anomaly flags across the window. From trace analysis productcatalogservice pods are downstream in call chains (receiving calls from checkoutservice and frontend) and are anomalous in both metrics and traces, making them high-priority root-cause candidates. To decide the underlying reason (e.g., container fs I/O vs. memory vs. CPU vs. node disk), logs for productcatalogservice pods during the incident window may contain corroborating evidence (I/O errors, OOM messages, throttling logs, or similar). The next step is to inspect normalized logs for productcatalogservice components in the incident window to look for relevant log indicators and to collect compact aggregates (counts and earliest occurrences) that point to an I/O/memory/CPU issue.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Filter log.csv to the incident window 2022-03-21 12:00:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 12:30:00+08:00 and to cmdb_id in [\"productcatalogservice\",\"productcatalogservice-0\",\"productcatalogservice-1\",\"productcatalogservice-2\",\"productcatalogservice2-0\"]. Store the filtered rows in kernel variable 'productcatalog_logs'. Then aggregate by log_name and compute: count, earliest_timestamp_UTC+8, and mean(value). Return two compact outputs only: \n1) Top 20 log_name rows sorted by count descending with columns: log_name, count, earliest_timestamp_UTC+8, mean_value. \n2) Up to 5 sample rows from 'productcatalog_logs' showing columns: timestamp_UTC+8, cmdb_id, log_name, value sorted by timestamp ascending. \nKeep outputs bounded and do not perform any further metric/trace joins in this step."
}
